  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Two Sum II - Input Array Is Sorted\n\nGiven a nondecreasing array `numbers`, return one-based indices of two different values that add to `target`.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: numbers = [1, 4, 6, 10, 13], target = 16\nOutput: [3, 4]\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: numbers = [-8, -3, 2, 5, 9], target = 1\nOutput: [2, 3]\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: numbers = [2, 7], target = 9\nOutput: [1, 2]\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- `2 <= len(numbers) <= 30000`\n- Exactly one valid pair exists.\n\n## Follow-up\n\nUse the sorted order directly.",
  "editorial": "Start with pointers at both ends. If the sum is too small, move the left pointer right. If the sum is too large, move the right pointer left.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def twoSum(self, numbers, target):\n        left, right = 0, len(numbers) - 1\n        while left < right:\n            total = numbers[left] + numbers[right]\n            if total == target:\n                return [left + 1, right + 1]\n            if total < target:\n                left += 1\n            else:\n                right -= 1\n```",
  "hints": [
    "The smallest remaining value is on the left.",
    "The largest remaining value is on the right."
  ],
  "starter_code": {
    "python": "class Solution:\n    def twoSum(self, numbers, target):\n        pass\n"
  },
  "entrypoint": {
